Data Description:¶

The data at hand contains medical costs of people characterized by certain attributes.¶

Domain:¶

Healthcare¶

Context:¶

Leveraging customer information is paramount for most businesses. In the case of an insurance company, attributes of customers like the ones mentioned below can be crucial in making business decisions. Hence, knowing to explore and generate value out of such data can be an invaluable skill to have.¶

Attribute Information:¶

age : age of primary beneficiary¶

sex : insurance contractor gender, female, male¶

bmi : Body mass index, providing an understanding of body,¶

weights that are relatively high or low relative to height,¶

objective index of body weight (kg / m ^ 2) using the ratio of¶

height to weight, ideally 18.5 to 24.9¶

children : Number of children covered by health insurance /¶

Number of dependents¶

smoker : Smoking¶

region : the beneficiary's residential area in the US, northeast,¶

southeast, southwest, northwest.¶

charges : Individual medical costs billed by health insurance.¶

Learning Outcomes:¶

● Exploratory Data Analysis¶

● Practicing statistics using Python¶

● Hypothesis testing¶

Objective:¶

We want to see if we can dive deep into this data to find some valuable insights.¶

Steps and tasks:¶

Statistics Test:¶

Ho : Charges of people who smoke do not differ from the people who don't¶

Ha : Charges of people who smoke differ significantly from the people who don't¶

Using T-Test:¶

In [31]:
t_statistics, p_value = ttest_ind(df_2['charges'],df_2['smoker']) #using ttest_ind() and passed 'charges' and 'smoker' columns
print('T-Statistic value:',t_statistics, '\nP-Value:', p_value)  #print t-value and p-values

if p_value > 0.05: # significance level is 0.05
    print('\033[1m''Fail to reject Null Hypothesis i.e. charges do not differ for smokers and non-smokers')
else:
    print('\033[1m''Reject Null Hypothesis i.e. charges differ for smokers and non-smokers')

T-Statistic value: 40.08312294525875 
P-Value: 1.5354226097474645e-275
Reject Null Hypothesis i.e. charges differ for smokers and non-smokers

There are two genders 'male' and 'female' respectively, based on this the hypothesis can be formed as below:¶

  • 'sex' and 'smoker' are two categorical variables
  • We want to see if the proportion of smokers in both gender different
  • 159 male smoke out of 676
  • 115 females smoke out of 662
  • Percentage of male smokers is higher than female

Ho = The proportion of smokers are equal in both genders¶

Ha = The two proportion of smokers are not equal in both genders¶

Using z-test:¶

In [38]:
female_smokers = df[df['sex'] == 'female'].smoker.value_counts()[1]  # number of female smokers
male_smokers = df[df['sex'] == 'male'].smoker.value_counts()[1] # number of male smokers
n_females = df.sex.value_counts()[1] # number of females in the data
n_males = df.sex.value_counts()[0] #number of males in the data
In [39]:
print([female_smokers, male_smokers] , [n_females, n_males])
print('\033[1m'f' Proportion of smokers in females, males = {round(115/662,2)}%, {round(159/676,2)}% respectively')

[115, 159] [676, 662]
 Proportion of smokers in females, males = 0.17%, 0.24% respectively

The proportions are different but are they statistically significant?¶

In [40]:
stat, pval = proportions_ztest([female_smokers, male_smokers] , [n_females, n_males]) #using ztest for proportion

if pval < 0.05:  
    print('\033[1m'f'With a p-value of {round(pval,4)} the difference is significant. Reject Null hypothesis i.e. Proportion of smokers across genders is different')
else:
    print('\033[1m'f'With a p-value of {round(pval,4)} the difference is not significant. Fail to reject Null hypothesis i.e. Proportion of smokers across genders is similar')

With a p-value of 0.0015 the difference is significant. Reject Null hypothesis i.e. Proportion of smokers across genders is different

Using Chi Square Test:¶

In [42]:
chi2_stats, p_value, dof, table = chi2_contingency(smoking_cross) #using chi-square test method

print('\033[1m''\nDegree of freedom:','%1.2f'% dof)
print('\033[1m''\nP-Value:','%1.2f'% p_value)

if p_value > 0.05:
    print('\033[1m''\nFail to reject Null hypothesis i.e. Proportion of smokers across genders is similar')
else:
    print('\n''\033[1m''Reject Null hypothesis i.e. Proportion of smokers across genders is different')

mc_table = MultiComparison(df['bmi'], df['children']) # Tests for multiple comparisons of bmi and children
result = mc_table.tukeyhsd() # Tukey’s range test to compare means of all pairs of bmi and children
print(result) # prints result table

print('Unique categories present in table:',mc_table.groupsunique) #prints multicomparision groups 

tukey_res = mc_table.tukeyhsd()
p_values = psturng(np.abs(tukey_res.meandiffs / tukey_res.std_pairs), len(tukey_res.groupsunique), tukey_res.df_total)
print("p values:", p_values)
